c type of language endangerment, documentation strategies, and other ethical issues pertaining to these sign languages on the basis of first-hand experiences by Deaf fieldworkers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aDeafxLanguage. 0aSign languagexCross-cultural studies. 0aSign language. 4aBedrohte Sprachen. 4aGebärdensprache. 4aSprachtypologie. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aEndangered Languages and Fieldwork.  aLanguage Typology.  aSign Language.  aVisual Communication.1 aAdone, Dany, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Anastasia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCumberbatch, Keren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDikyuva, Hasan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKisch, Shifra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusters, Annelies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLanesman, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe Guen, Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagassouba, Moustapha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaypilama, Elaine L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeir, Irit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNonaka, Angela M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyst, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchuit, Joke, econtri